  "prompt": "What is the difference between enum, union and struct in C programming?",
  "response": "In C programming, `enum`, `union`, and `struct` are three distinct types of user-defined data structures, each serving different purposes and having unique characteristics:\n\n### Enum (Enumeration):\n1. **Purpose**: \n   - An `enum` is primarily used to define a variable that can hold a set of predefined constant integer values. These values represent different states or options and make the code more readable.\n\n2. **Usage**:\n   - You define an `enum` using the `enum` keyword followed by a set of named integer constants.\n   - For example:\n     ```c\n     enum Color { RED, GREEN, BLUE };\n     ```\n\n3. **Characteristics**:\n   - By default, the values assigned to the enumeration constants start from 0 and increase by 1, unless explicitly specified otherwise.\n   - Enums improve code readability and maintainability by using meaningful names instead of simple integers.\n\n### Union:\n1. **Purpose**:\n   - A `union` allows storing different data types in the same memory location. It can contain multiple members, but only one of them can hold a value at any given time.\n\n2. **Usage**:\n   - You define a `union` using the `union` keyword followed by a list of members.\n   - For example:\n     ```c\n     union Data {\n         int i;\n         float f;\n         char c;\n     };\n     ```\n\n3. **Characteristics**:\n   - A union provides a way to use the same memory location for different purposes at different times, which is useful in situations where you want to optimize memory usage.\n   - The size of a union is determined by the size of its largest member, since all members share the same memory location.\n   - Changing the value of one member will affect the other members, as they overlap in memory.\n\n### Struct (Structure):\n1. **Purpose**:\n   - A `struct` is used to group different data types into a single unit. Unlike `union`, all members of a `struct` have their own memory space.\n\n2. **Usage**:\n   - You define a `struct` using the `struct` keyword followed by a set of member variables.\n   - For example:\n     ```c\n     struct Point {\n         int x;\n         int y;\n     };\n     ```\n\n3. **Characteristics**:\n   - Each member of a struct has its own memory allocation, making it possible to store multiple values simultaneously.\n   - The size of a struct is the sum of the sizes of its members, taking into account any padding introduced for alignment purposes.\n   - Structs are useful for modeling complex data structures that need to hold various types of data together.\n\nIn summary, `enum` is for defining symbolic names for sets of related integer values, `union` is for data that can be one of many types at different times, and `struct` is for grouping different data types together.",
  "response_tokens": [
